node.text: Comedian @nikkiglaser has built a career on being unapologetically honest and herself. Listen as she and host @therealjencohen discuss her ups and downs, how the pandemic impacted her and her work, cancel culture, dating, dieting, and more. Listen to full episodes of #habitsandhustle on Apple Podcasts.

node.title: Habits and Hustle with Jen Cohen: Nikki Glaser

node.text:
Entrepreneur's @heyfeifer chats with Chef @priavanda, head chef and owner of NYC-restaurant @desigalli, about how she kept her restaurant open and launch two new businesses during lockdown.

PriaVanda is also featured at the Boost with Facebook Good Ideas Festival, a virtual celebration of small businesses. The Festival will offer inspiration and education for small businesses all over the world. You can learn more about it at Fb.com/goodideasfestival.

node.text:

node.title: Succeed by Staying Flexible in Business

node.text:
Many founders (if not all founders) experience self-doubt. So how do you keep going when the voices around you (and sometimes in your head) are telling you that you're on a fast track to failure?

@nicolewalters, founder and CEO of @inheritlearning, chats with @nicolegibbonsstyle, founder and CEO of @clarepaint, about overcoming self-doubt when starting a business. (Brought to you by @delltech)

node.title: Building Confidence While Building Your Business

node.title: How to Find the Right People to Power Your Small Business

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Entrepreneur on August 09, 2021 tagging @testmyhome. May be an image of 1 person, sitting and outdoors.

node.text:
What advice would you give entrepreneurs looking for funding?

"I’m a believer in letting money follow your passion. If you do something you love really well, people and money will find you. Everyone is in a rush to get funding when instead they should just focus on doing a job really well. When you get paid to do something you love, your work no longer becomes a job and getting paid to do it becomes very rewarding. Teddy Roosevelt once said, “Do all that you can do, with whatever you have, wherever you are.” Focus on that and money will find you." - Ryan Blaser, CEO and co-founder of @testmyhome. (link in bio for full article)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Entrepreneur on August 06, 2021 tagging @michaelcitywinery, and @citywinerynyc. May be an image of 1 person and standing.

node.text:
"When you're an entrepreneur and going quickly down class-four rapids and you're not in a boat, your feet better be in front of you, because you're gonna be bouncing off these rocks, and they're just going to appear. So you could have this whole pivot where people saw it coming and had a meeting and moved around and decided to change from being an online company to a social media platform, and then when they saw that that wasn't gonna work, they went back into the 'real world' of hospitality or something. Pivoting to me is dodging what could be fatal crashes and figuring out a way to avoid them." - @michaelcitywinery, founder of @citywinerynyc.

The hospitality innovator lays out five ways business owners can weather recessions, pandemics and the perils of being broke. (link in bio)

node.text:
This TikTok Star's First-Ever Podcast, Downloaded Over a Million Times, Knocks Dave Ramsey's and Joe Rogan's Down the Chart 

Unlike many of the popular business podcasts that Financial Feminist has knocked down the charts, Dunlap’s show approaches personal-finance conversations from a more nuanced perspective. “We're not just talking about the individual choices that you can make to better your money,” Dunlap says. “Because, unfortunately, those are limited. We're talking about these larger systemic issues that keep women and other marginalized groups from building wealth or from creating businesses or from paying off their debt or from having choices."

Tori Dunlap (@herfirst100k), a 27-year-old personal-finance educator and multimillion-dollar business owner, launched 'Financial Feminist' in May. Within 72 hours, her podcast was No. 1 on Apple Business charts. Read more at the link in bio.

“It’s so important to remember that you are the CEO of your own life. It’s the most important job you will ever have. You are responsible for your happiness, your career, and your success!” 

You should never be afraid to take charge of your life and make a change when you see fit. Have you been wanting to make a change, but aren’t sure what it should be?
